export const batch120 = {
  'co-intelligence-living-and-working-with-ai.json': {
    base: { id: 'co-intelligence-living-and-working-with-ai', title: 'Co-Intelligence', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781612682838 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A new way of working with machines',
        text: 'Most people think AI should act like normal software, and that is a mistake. Regular programs follow strict rules and always give the same answer. AI works in a different way. Its results can be wild and uneven. Sometimes it offers surprising new ideas, and other times it slips up or seems to forget what it knows.\n\nAI can sound confident about its choices, but it does not really think the way people do. Old software comes with thick manuals that explain everything. AI gives no such guide.\n\nResearchers now study AI the same way they study people. Just as income and life events shape how a person shops, the training data and code shape how an AI behaves. Companies once spent huge sums learning what makes people buy. Now they are doing the same thing for AI.\n\nWhen AI is trained well, it can read a room and make value-based calls almost like a person. Treating AI like a person makes the work easier. Picture a marketing director who needs taglines for a new watch. A bare request gets bland lines. But ask the AI to play the part of a comedian and the answers get fun and original.\n\nThere is a flip side to this habit. Some users start to think the machine has feelings. They share personal details without realizing a company runs the tool.\n\nGiving human traits to nonhuman things has a name. We see faces in clouds, talk to our pets, and blame the weather for a bad day. So it is normal to chat with AI the way you would chat with a friend. Just remember that AI is not a person. Do not share anything you would not tell a stranger on the street.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A long history of thinking machines',
        text: 'The dream of a thinking machine is older than you might guess. Back in the 1700s, a device called the Mechanical Turk wowed crowds by playing chess. Ben Franklin and Napoleon both watched it in wonder. People thought it could think, but the truth was a hidden chess master inside moved the pieces.\n\nThe 1900s brought fresh ideas. In 1950, Claude Shannon built a small robot mouse called Theseus that could learn its way through a maze. Around the same time, Alan Turing proposed a test to see if a machine could fool a person. These early steps set the stage for modern AI.\n\nCuriosity is the engine of progress in this field. Researchers once thought smart machines would arrive in a few short years. When that did not happen, funding dried up. The slow periods became known as AI winters.\n\nThe 2010s brought AI back to life. Big firms like Amazon used it to forecast demand and run smoother operations.\n\nIn 2017, a research paper titled "Attention Is All You Need" changed the game. A team at Google introduced the Transformer, a new design that helps AI focus on the parts of a text that matter most. This leap made AI much better at reading and writing human language.\n\nTraining these models costs a fortune. It takes powerful machines that read billions of words and learn from them. The first version of ChatGPT had 175 billion settings for understanding language. Newer models like GPT-4 are even bigger.\n\nEven with all that training, AI can still be fooled. Clever prompts can trick it into giving harmful answers, like instructions for dangerous chemicals.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A different kind of software',
        text: 'Treating AI like old software leads to wrong expectations. Tested software obeys strict rules and gives the same output each time. AI does not work that way. Its answers can be hit or miss. One run may bring a clever new idea, and the next may stumble or forget.\n\nAI can talk through its choices in a smooth way, but it lacks true reflection. Classic software ships with detailed guides. AI offers no manual.\n\nSocial scientists now treat AI like a person in their studies. The same forces that shape human spending, like income and life experience, shape an AI model through its data and code. Firms once spent fortunes mapping the human mind. Now they map AI in the same way.\n\nA well trained AI can pick up on social cues and make calls based on values, much like a person can. It helps to picture AI as a coworker. A marketing director who needs watch slogans will get bland lines from a flat prompt. Ask the AI to act like a stand up comic, and the slogans get playful and bold.\n\nThe same habit carries risks. Some people start to think the machine cares about them. They hand over private details to what is really a company product.\n\nThe habit of giving human traits to nonhuman things runs deep. We spot faces in clouds, talk to our pets, and swear at the rain. It feels natural to do the same with AI, since chatting with it feels like chatting with a friend. The key reminder is that AI is not human. Do not share with it anything you would not share with a stranger.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A fast partner for ideas and analysis',
        text: 'AI can crank out ideas at high speed. Give GPT-4 a simple creativity test and it can list over 100 uses for a toothbrush in under two minutes. No human can keep up. This pace shows that AI thinks along paths people may not try.\n\nStill, the originality of AI raises tough questions. AI does not pull from a single library. It blends patterns from its training, so its work can echo things that already exist. An AI may copy a famous painter style without the meaning behind the original.\n\nThe future of work means using AI well while keeping its risks in view. AI is not just quick on paper tasks. In a Wharton contest, AI beat 200 students by producing more and stronger ideas for a cheap product. That win shows AI is a strong brainstorming partner, especially for people who get stuck on their own.\n\nAI also helps with code and data. It can write software, lower the bar for new coders, and pull themes from huge piles of data for fields like finance. A team at the University of Chicago found that AI could read company earnings calls and predict stock swings better than specialist models.\n\nThese gifts come with a cost. Heavy reliance on AI can dull human creativity and block learning. AI can also make stuff up, a quirk often called hallucination, which is risky when the facts matter.\n\nThe person in the loop has to check the AI for made up facts and lies. By pouring out ideas fast, AI frees people to refine and remix those ideas. That blend is where real breakthroughs tend to land.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A new shape for daily work',
        text: 'AI is changing what work looks like. Past automation hit factory and farm jobs. Now AI is reshaping creative and skilled work. College professors sit near the top of the list for tasks AI can touch. Their jobs will not vanish, but the tasks inside them will shift a lot.\n\nAI is great at narrow, routine, and admin jobs. A business professor can hand report writing to AI and get hours back for teaching. The role is still there, but it looks very different. Power tools did not replace carpenters, and AI will not replace most workers.\n\nJobs live inside complex systems, so AI cannot take them over on its own. Even if AI could teach a class, schools, students, and the value of human contact all still matter.\n\nThe path forward is a blend of human skill and AI power. The idea of a Jagged Frontier helps explain this. Some tasks are easy for AI, like brainstorming. Others, like basic math, can trip it up. The line keeps moving, so people need to keep testing.\n\nMany things that seemed only human can now be done by AI. A growing trend is what some call secret task automation. Workers use AI to speed up their day without telling the boss. Office rules against AI push people underground. Job loss fears add to the silence.\n\nThe smart move for firms is to use AI to make work better, not to cut headcount. Research from the IDC projects AI spending in Europe will pass 50 billion dollars by 2025.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A new way to help each student',
        text: 'Tutors have always helped students more than any other method. In 1984, an education researcher named Benjamin Bloom called this the 2 Sigma Problem. His studies showed that students with personal tutors beat most of their peers. A tutored student often lands ahead of 98 percent of a regular class. The catch has always been cost and the challenge of giving every student their own tutor.\n\nAI can help close that gap. It cannot take the place of a real teacher, but it can give each student personal support. AI tutors adapt to the learner and offer quick feedback.\n\nSome people worry classrooms will fade away. The more likely story is that AI makes classrooms more valuable. By handling tasks like lectures and grading, AI gives teachers room to teach creativity, critical thinking, and teamwork.\n\nAI also gives teachers clear data on how each student learns. That insight helps shape lessons, mark struggling students, and build a more engaging room.\n\nWhen AI personalizes the prep, students walk in ready for hands on work. Real tools are already here. Khan Academy launched Khanmigo, an AI tutor that goes past videos and quizzes. It lets students learn by talking through ideas, which helps them remember more.\n\nThere is a dark side. AI has made cheating easier, a problem some call the Homework Apocalypse. Schools will need to balance old methods with new AI tools. The goal is to design tasks that push students to use AI in smart, honest ways.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A future built with people and machines',
        text: 'No matter how AI spreads, human skill will still matter most. As AI takes on more tasks, people need to grow new skills and focus on the work only humans can do well.\n\nThat shift can open fresh roles. People and AI will work side by side to reach higher goals.\n\nA good first step is to try AI tools like ChatGPT and Google Gemini. Get a feel for how they think. Keep up with AI news in your field so you can plan your next move. Other Headway summaries like Life 3.0 by Max Tegmark and AI Superpowers by Kai-Fu Lee offer more depth on AI and human minds.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'colorful-management.json': {
    base: { id: 'colorful-management', title: 'Colorful Management', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781612767638 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Living side by side in different worlds',
        text: 'Each person carries their own mix of values, priorities, thoughts, and growth. Together they shape how we act, lead, and talk. That mix is called a paradigm of thinking. As people and societies change, paradigms change too. This idea lives inside a model called integral dynamics, which is the base for the ideas in this summary.\n\nIntegral dynamics says that our thinking grows in stages, and each stage shifts what we care about. No single paradigm is better than another. Each one shines in its own setting.\n\nA paradigm is the set of core values and habits that drive how we think. It shapes our actions.\n\nParadigms live in people, firms, and even whole countries. They mirror the dominant view of the group. That is why different workplaces and leadership styles fit different paradigms. The next sections look at well known paradigms and how they shape work.\n\nSo why does any of this matter? The short answer is to build understanding. Crossing the gap between people with different paradigms can be hard. We share space but live in different worlds, because paradigms act as quiet filters that shape what we see.\n\nEach paradigm gives a full and steady view of the world, a complete take on what exists and what happens. Until a key moment, no one spots the flaws in their own view when talking to someone from another view, as author Valerii Pekar notes.\n\nFrom birth, we move through these stages. Most people pass through some, but not all. The path depends on life events and personal growth. Philosopher Ken Wilber paints a picture of a wide river. We start at the same bank, but we end in different places. Our tools and skills shape where we land. Some swim, some paddle, and some fear the water.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The earliest stages of human thought',
        text: 'For the sake of memory, this summary uses colors to mark each paradigm. There are six clear paradigms so far, a seventh on the horizon, and an eighth that is still a theory.\n\nHumanity keeps evolving in how it thinks, the same way Charles Darwin described for the body. That evolution brings new paradigms.\n\nThe earliest stage is the beige world, which runs on pure instinct. Survival is the only goal in a harsh setting where basic needs are tough to meet. People in deep crisis, like homelessness, addiction, or severe brain injury, often live in this paradigm. About 0.1 percent of adults sit here. War, disaster, and bad leaders can push anyone into it. Infants touch this stage briefly before moving on to purple.\n\nThe purple world feels safer and runs on shared rules that meet the group needs. People in this stage often believe in magic and ritual. They follow many rules and have a weak sense of self. The group matters more than the person, and loyalty rules. About 10 percent of people live here. The pull of a calm childhood is strong, but staying too long holds you back.\n\nThe next stage is the red world. Red turns the focus back to the self and the ego. People here chase fast pleasure and prize strength, cunning, and power. This stage grew up with farming, when food and goods gave the ability to sway others. About 20 percent of the global population sits in red. Teens, tyrants, criminals, corrupt cops, and shady politicians all show up here. Every child passes through a red phase when they test the limits of self. Red may look harsh, but it is a normal part of growth and not a flaw.'
      },
      {
        title: 'When new problems bring new views',
        text: 'A big shift in thinking comes with the blue world. Here people look for peace and a higher purpose, guided by firm rules and a system of reward and punishment. Blue prizes morality, law, and order. Deep faith or strong ideology drive it, and the focus is on how one believes more than what one believes. Blue covers about 40 percent of people, which makes it the most common paradigm.\n\nWhen blue order blocks progress, the orange paradigm steps in. Orange acts like a machine. It is fully rational and offers plenty of chances to grow. Orange has no single truth, but it always offers a choice. Success rules the day, and material signs of status matter most. Founders, scientists, and artists often live here. Rooted in the Enlightenment and fed by the Industrial Revolution, orange covers about 30 percent of people today.\n\nThere are more blues in the world than oranges, yet almost all wealth and power sit with the orange crowd. The green world is newer and stands for harmony, humanism, spirit, and care for others. Green puts healthy relationships ahead of personal success. Its people welcome differences and push for equal worth. Movements like environmentalism, social justice, and equal rights all carry a green tone. Less than 10 percent of people live here.\n\nGreen is great in many ways, but it moves slowly. That pace pushes restless doers into the yellow world. Yellow is a complex second order realm that blends the strengths of all the earlier stages. Yellow people adapt fast, shift roles, and switch views with ease. Independence, dignity, and freedom are the core values. Yellows aim to grow themselves and help others. They solve problems fast and think big. Only 1 percent of people reach yellow, and they stand out for their mix of charm and skill.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Why growth and movement never stop',
        text: 'Now that the paradigms are clearer, the next question is how people, firms, and even whole nations move along this rainbow. The shift from one world to the next is slow, not a quick jump. This section looks at the path between worlds and the general pattern of change.\n\nOne key pattern stands out. Paradigms move in a zigzag, swinging back and forth between the group and the self, and between the material and the ideal. Beige focuses on self survival, purple on the group. Red swings back to the self, blue to the group. The swing keeps going, but each loop reaches a higher, more complex level.\n\nMore complex life often comes with growth. The color worlds rarely show up in pure form. They mix and overlap. Moving from one to the next is hard, which is why only about a third of people reach orange. Some do not feel the push to grow, while others lack the chance.\n\nStill, the march forward is vital. Each new stage gives tools to handle old problems and face new ones.\n\nYou cannot solve a problem on the same level that it was created. You have to rise above it to the next level, as Albert Einstein put it. No matter where you stand on the path, you do not have to tick off each world like a list. Older paradigms stay useful, like rings in a tree trunk. They live in the same mind and support each other. It is wise to learn how to call on each one when it fits. You can draw on red when facing a robber and blue when you need to set order.\n\nThe trick is to know each paradigm and learn to switch them on when needed. By the way, the color names follow a pattern. Warm shades mark individualistic worlds, while cool shades mark those that lean toward the group.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Matching people to the right work',
        text: 'The world is full of colors, and each paradigm asks for its own approach. Adapting to the colors around you can be tough, especially inside teams and firms. Each paradigm needs a different style of teaching, goal setting, and motivation. A good leader reads those needs and sets people up to do their best. That is how a company hits peak output.\n\nRule one is simple. Not everyone is built for the spotlight. Each person has their own mix of skills, knowledge, and traits, and the paradigm shapes it most. The split is rough, but it helps us sort the colors.\n\nEveryone should do the work that matches their nature, and employees in the right role enjoy their job, as Valerii Pekar writes. Different people need different handling. Red workers do best with clear simple tasks and do not bring much personal drive. They respond to firm correction. Blue workers follow detailed tasks without much oversight. They need only a mentor, and they thrive on praise. Orange workers can handle complex projects on their own. Give them a goal, the right tools, and room to find their way. They like to innovate and value feedback. Green workers excel at long term goals and big team projects. They are rare, so hiring them is hard. Yellow workers pick their own goals and direction, which makes them tough to manage. Their output depends on the fit with the work. Purple workers tend to react to the task in front of them. They are rare and form the core of farming, but they can be tough to lead.\n\nWhen a manager knows what each color can do, they can place people in the right seat. The right fit lets any worker show their strengths and add real value to the team. There is no single best paradigm. Every firm needs a mix of types across its teams and stages.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The right culture for the right team',
        text: 'Just as people carry their own paradigm, so do firms and groups. This section looks at the culture of a company, the paradigm inside its walls.\n\nThe culture of a firm is the set of principles, norms, and rules its people follow. When a firm culture clashes with your paradigm, even a great job can feel wrong. Comfort and fit matter as much as pay and status. The next paragraphs cover the main types of management culture, so you can spot the one that fits you or your team.\n\nPurple organizations are rare, much like purple workers. They build a strong sense of belonging, almost like a family, with a clear leader and tight informal bonds. This style shows up in small family firms and new start ups, where trust and devotion drive the work.\n\nRed organizations run on raw power. One strong leader makes the calls and rules the structure. There is no real democracy, and the whole firm depends on that one person. Red works in a crisis, but it blocks growth and learning over time.\n\nBlue organizations rely on clear chains of command and firm rules. These bureaucratic groups set strict steps for every process. Blue fits large institutions like churches, government agencies, and firms in stable fields. The setting is safe and the path up the ladder is clear.\n\nOrange organizations chase success and prize results over hierarchy. These modern firms value the employee experience and feed off a shared drive to win. Every voice counts, and everyone shapes the call. Orange teams are flexible, fast, and ready to adapt.\n\nGreen organizations live in the non profit world. They have no formal hierarchy, and each voice carries equal weight. A unique feature is shared leadership, where team members take turns at the top. The base of these teams is harmony, deep trust, and the joy of working well together.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A world made richer by variety',
        text: 'Where can we find the perfect leader? Integral dynamics says there is none. Each style has its own fit, and it lines up with certain situations, firms, types of workers, and stages of growth.\n\nThe world is richer because it is varied, and the colorful paradigms are a clear sign of that mix. To live a vivid, full life, we have to welcome variety, both inside and out.\n\nIntegral dynamics shows up in work and in personal growth, but the reach is much wider. Politics, the economy, the military, faith, and identity all feel the pull of paradigms. Human thought keeps moving, and that motion drives real change in every corner of life. Watching the shift is useful, because it makes sense of what is happening around us and points to the next step.\n\nWe sit high on the ladder of evolution, but the climb is not over. Human awareness keeps growing. Each push for self growth adds a small piece to the larger rise of the universe. That is reason enough to keep aiming high.\n\nA useful first step is to think about the paradigms that shape your own life and actions. Rate the impact of each color on you and your surroundings on a scale of one to ten. The biggest gaps between you and your world are often the source of discomfort.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'commander-in-cheat.json': {
    base: { id: 'commander-in-cheat', title: 'Commander In Cheat', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781656845968 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The mindset behind the game',
        text: 'Donald Trump has always cared more about sounding good than being right. For him, truth is a soft gray area, and he does not seem to mind when fact checkers call him out.\n\nBack in 2015, a friend of the author shared a dinner with Donald and Melania Trump. Couples drifted into side chats during the meal. One of the women told Melania her accent was lovely and asked where she was from. Melania said Slovenia. Donald cut in from his own chat and said, "Tell her Austria. It sounds better."\n\nThere was also his 2013 post aimed at Mark Cuban. Trump bragged he had won 18 club championships. A check of the claim showed that all 18 came from golf courses he owned and had just opened. Even then, 16 of those titles were flat lies, and the other two could not be confirmed.\n\nPlay golf with a man to see his real character, as P. G. Wodehouse once wrote.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A long line of golfing presidents',
        text: 'Many past US presidents loved the game. The White House can feel like a gilded prison with butlers, and the chief resident cannot leave without a week of planning and a squad of agents in tow. Golf was a perfect release.\n\nWilliam Howard Taft once made the president of Chile wait while he teed off. Woodrow Wilson took up the game on doctor advice and got hooked, going so far as to paint his golf balls black so he could play in the snow. Warren Harding was a joy on the course and died of heart failure in San Francisco, his favorite golf city. Calvin Coolidge was not much of a player. Franklin Roosevelt may have been the most gifted golfing president. He won medals as a teen and the Campobello club title, and he left a public legacy that included Bethpage, the New York course that hosted the 2019 PGA Championship. Dwight Eisenhower loved the game and was a close friend of Arnold Palmer. He had a putting green put in near the Oval Office so he could practice. Lyndon Johnson used golf to win political support, and legend has it he gathered the votes to pass the Civil Rights Act on the course.\n\nLater presidents joined in. Nixon played to an 18 handicap in office and a 12 after he resigned. Gerald Ford was not much of a player. George H. Bush was an 18 handicap who could finish in two hours. Bill Clinton took his time on the course, six hours a round was nothing, and he was good company for the slow walk. George W. Bush played to a 15 and was a friend of Ben Crenshaw, who said the Bushes do not cheat. Obama played to an 11, did not cheat, and liked private rounds with sportswriters. Donald Trump rounds out the list.\n\nTrump does more than play. He builds, buys, owns, runs, sues over, lies about, and brags about his courses. Golf shapes the people he knows, the deals he cuts, the favors he hands out, the trouble he gets into, the places he goes, the money he makes and loses, and even the views in his head.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How the cheat was born',
        text: 'Donald Trump picked up golf with real hunger while at the Wharton School at Penn. He played at Cobbs Creek, a public course full of gamblers, hustlers, and laid off steel workers. The course was a short drive from campus.\n\nAt Cobbs Creek, every moment around a round came with a bet. If one player could think up a wager, another would take it. Trump learned the game in that stew. He played his friends and then the hustlers. He bet, won some, and lost some.\n\nAt Cobbs Creek, he built the swing that sends the ball flat along the ground, and he soaked up the hustler mind set.\n\nSeveral people who know his game were asked to rate it. His longtime caddie put him at a solid 7. Pro player Brad Faxon called him a legit 10. Four time major winner Ernie Els said 8 or 9. LPGA great Annika Sörenstam said 9 or 10.\n\nDonald Trump says he is a 2.8. So Donald Trump cheats at golf. As a member of Winged Foot, caddies called him Pele because he allegedly kicked his ball back into the fairway. Dr. Lance Dodes, a Harvard psychiatrist and coauthor of The Dangerous Case of Donald Trump, has said Trump shows signs of a narcissistic personality disorder. A constant need to be the best, and a refusal to lose or look like less than the best, runs through his behavior, as Dodes put it.\n\nIf Trump cheats at golf, it follows that he cheats in business, taxes, politics, with his wife, and in his net worth, his crowd sizes, his weight, and even the height of his buildings.\n\nIn life, we are defined by the obstacles we overcome. If you cheat to get around them, you never know the thrill of beating them for real, as Rick Reilly wrote.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A closer look at the course claims',
        text: 'Donald Trump has called his collection the greatest in the history of golf, a set of 14 courses by the end of 2018. The courses are nice, but they are not as great as he says.\n\nMost of the land they sit on was bought cheap, with Trump himself once saying 10 to 15 cents on the dollar, and much of it has been in default or went bankrupt. In the 2019 to 2020 edition of Golf Digest Top 100 American Courses, none of Trump properties made the list, even when they did well in the overall ranking. Trump International in West Palm Beach sat at 178 in America. Trump Turnberry took 10th in the world. Trump International at Aberdeen was 64th worldwide.\n\nThe real top spot goes to Mike Keiser, the owner of Bandon Dunes in Oregon. All four of his courses there sit on the Top 100 list.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A cold welcome in Scotland',
        text: 'Donald Trump has family roots in Scotland, and many Scots dislike him for it. There are at least two reasons.\n\nFirst, his grasp of UK and island geography is weak. He once suggested Ireland was part of the UK and that Scotland was a country apart from it. On Brexit, he said Scotland took their country back. They did not. Scotland voted 62 percent against Brexit.\n\nThe other reason is golf. In 2006, Trump set out to build a luxury public resort near Balmedie, just north of Aberdeen. The site was the Menie Estate, an old shooting ranch he had picked up for 11 million dollars. The plan called for two courses, an eight story five star hotel with 450 rooms, a sports complex, 950 time share units, and 36 villas. All of this sat on a stretch of live dunes marked as a Site of Special Scientific Interest, the highest grade of protection in Scotland.\n\nThe fight became a standoff, captured in the documentary You Have Been Trumped. Today, only one of the two planned courses has been built. No hotel, no time share units, no 6,000 new jobs, and no 1.28 billion dollars for the local economy. Trump family roots in Scotland pushed back hard and won.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Breaking every rule of the game',
        text: 'President Trump is famous for breaking political norms, and golf gave him decades of practice.\n\nGolf etiquette asks players to take off their hats for the end of round handshake and in the clubhouse. Donald Trump does not.\n\nNo matter whose turn it is, Trump steps up first and hits. He hates to lose. After losing a 50 dollar bet to a member at Winged Foot, he bad mouthed the man for cashing the check instead of framing it.\n\nDonald Trump does not walk, and that breaks a core aim of the game. He drives his cart right onto the greens, a serious breach. Caddies do not even set the bag on the green because it leaves tire marks that can steer putts off line.\n\nTrump also drives across tee boxes and plays through groups without asking. He also pressures golf magazines to rate his courses well. He fumes when other courses rank higher or when his own get no rank at all. To explain the missing ranks, he falsely claims the policy is to spare his members any hassle.\n\nThe truth is he wants those lists, but ranking is one thing he cannot buy or bully his way into, and that drives him mad.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A round with the President',
        text: 'Say you get an invite to tee off with President Trump. Here is what to expect.\n\nFirst, you will play one of his own courses. Since taking office, he has played only at his own places, even passing up Winged Foot, where he is a member.\n\nGet ready for a round like no other. Expect protesters near the gate. Because the President only plays his own courses, protests are a regular sight. When you arrive, you will be sent to the locker room to change shoes and drink Trump coffee, Trump vodka, or Trump water, all now out of business. After that, you will head to the range for warm up shots.\n\nTrump will greet you with a 20 second pull you in handshake, his left hand on your right shoulder. Be warned. He does not practice much.\n\nGet ready for the heavy security. As many as 60 Secret Service agents, 6 SWAT team members, and 30 carts can appear, with staff carrying the nuclear football, the assistant chief of staff, a doctor with vials of the President blood, a comms aide, a secure satellite phone, a one man portable bomb shelter, gas masks, machine guns, weapons, and a small missile, all rolling along as you play. If you look closely, you may spot four camouflaged Marines with machine guns hidden in the brush near the fence line.\n\nExpect a fire truck, an ambulance, around ten black SUVs, police cars, and dogs staged near the club.\n\nAs play begins, you may see guests on the fairway being patted down, and you will play through them without asking. You may see the same in the dining room after the round if the President happens to be eating there.\n\nExpect a fast moving round. Do not expect deep talk with the President. Do not expect to know anyone score. Above all, expect him to win, fair or not. He is, after all, the President of the United States.'
      },
      {
        title: 'From the course to the country',
        text: 'Many of the problems and calls that have marked Donald Trump time in office can be traced back to his golf.\n\nThere are a few clear examples. In 2008, the Trump Organization pitched a plan to manage the Coco Beach Golf and Country Club, about 30 minutes from San Juan, Puerto Rico. The club was losing about 5.4 million dollars a year, and Trump promised to turn it around.\n\nAfter Trump took over, losses rose to 6.3 million dollars a year, including the 600,000 dollar fee the Trump Organization pulled out.\n\nSeven years later, and after pushing the Coco Beach Company into 33 million dollars of government loans, the Trump Organization declared bankruptcy on its piece of the project in 2015. Coco Beach Company folded, and Puerto Ricans were left holding a 33 million dollar debt.\n\nIn 2017, a fierce hurricane tore across the island and took out most of the infrastructure. Puerto Ricans went without power and water for eight months. Three thousand people lost their lives in the crisis. The federal government under Trump was nowhere to be found.\n\nThe so called travel ban on Muslim countries is another case. The plan called for blocking U.S. entry by citizens of Iran, Iraq, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria, and Yemen, on the grounds of a terror threat. Americans asked why the United Arab Emirates, a known funder of the Taliban, and Saudi Arabia, the source of many terror recruits, were left off the list. Why was Indonesia, where domestic terror in a single year can kill more than all global terror combined, also left off?\n\nCould the reason be the Trump International Golf Club Dubai and the Trump World Golf Club Dubai? Could it be his well known business ties to Saudi royals? Could it be that the Trump Organization was about to open two courses in Bali and Jakarta?\n\nTrump ran on a Buy American, Hire American line. Yet once in office, he signed an order raising the number of H 2B temporary visa workers allowed into the United States. Could that be because the Trump Organization staffs its courses and hotels with H 2B workers?\n\nTrump is friends with world leaders who play golf, like Japan Shinzo Abe, and cool to those who do not, like China Xi Jinping and Germany Angela Merkel. Since he took office, he has put at least five members of his own golf courses into serious roles in his administration.\n\nNearly every call the President makes seems to touch his wealth. There is a sense that lobbyists, special interest dealers, and foreign go betweens can win his attention by paying the entry fee at one of his clubs or by hosting events at his properties.\n\nPast presidents gave up possible conflicts of interest before taking office. Trump kept his business ties, saying Don, Eric, and Ivanka will be running things while he serves.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The high cost of winning at any price',
        text: 'Winning is good. Winning at any cost is not.\n\nDonald Trump shows the win at all costs mind set that runs through many narcissists. In his drive to win and stay on top, he shows the flaws that put him at odds with core American values, even as he holds the office of the President.\n\nA useful exercise is to list three to five traits of Trump the narcissist that you can unlearn in your own life. Also, several of his businesses have benefited in cash and kind from his time in office. Is that true or false, and can you back it up with clear reasons? Finally, why is it vital for a sitting President to step away from any source of conflict of interest? How does such a conflict get in the way of doing the constitutional job?'
      }
    ]
  },
  'como-mandar-a-la-mierda-de-forma-educada.json': {
    base: { id: 'como-mandar-a-la-mierda-de-forma-educada', title: 'How to Politely Tell People to F*ck Off', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781612838062 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'What a boundary really is',
        text: 'We hear the word boundary a lot, but what does it really mean? A boundary is a real or symbolic line that marks the space between you and another person. In psychology, personal boundaries are rules that protect your emotions, body, and mind in relationships, and each kind guards a different part of your life.\n\nBoundaries are not always easy to spot or speak about. Many people grow up putting the needs of others first. Some feel bad about correcting others for things that bother them.\n\nThere are several types of boundaries. Physical ones set how much contact you allow. Some people greet everyone with a hug, while a handshake feels like enough to others. Personal space covers privacy and personal items. Emotional boundaries shape how you show feelings and how others read them. Sexual boundaries cover the emotional, talk based, and physical parts of close relationships. Temporal boundaries protect the time you set aside for yourself and others. Material ones cover private ownership of things and the choice to share them.\n\nWhen you clearly say what you want and need, the other person knows how to act, as author Alba Cardalda puts it. Boundaries let you share what you want or need in any relationship. They are not just about telling others what to do. They are a way to care for your needs while still respecting the other person. Because they are personal and emotional, fair boundaries should not be judged. Respecting a boundary means accepting that other people have needs that differ from yours, even if that means admitting you will not always get along.\n\nAll limits fall into one of two big groups. Non negotiable boundaries come from values, principles, and dignity. They cover basics like no violence, mutual respect, and honesty. They must never be crossed, and a breach must bring clear, fast results. Negotiable boundaries allow more wiggle room. They are tied to personality or taste, and they do not hurt your body or mind if they shift. The key with these is to reach a mutual deal and adjust as needed. Clear boundaries protect your dignity and lead to honest, respectful relationships.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Working through the guilt',
        text: 'Setting a boundary can feel strange at first, and you may worry about feeling guilty. Guilt is a strong tool that has been used for ages, in society and in private life, to control and manipulate.\n\nWithout clear thinking and free thought, a society is open to manipulation. The same holds for personal ties, where someone who lacks emotional awareness can be pushed around with guilt or fear. The cycle breaks when you build emotional intelligence, so you can spot when someone is trying to control you and respond in kind.\n\nGuilt shows up in two main forms. Healthy or adaptive guilt is what you feel when you know you have made a mistake. It matches the harm done, and it pushes you to fix the damage and avoid a repeat. Unhealthy or maladaptive guilt is what you feel when you have done nothing wrong. It eats at your self esteem and does not help you grow.\n\nSpotting guilt helps you break free of old patterns and build healthier ties.\n\nSetting boundaries is frustrating and can flop at first. The people around you may read you wrong, and the first reaction can be rough. The only way past guilt is to smooth the process with practice. You will mess up, and that is fine. Accepting it makes the load lighter.\n\nAs you sharpen your emotional intelligence and your boundary setting, you will find a more flexible style that makes it easier to move from where you are to where you want to be. There are four main styles of communication when you set a boundary. Passive communicators struggle to defend their rights and put others first. They do not share feelings and treat them as unimportant. Aggressive communicators defend only their own rights with no thought for others. Their tone is hostile and lacks empathy. Passive aggressive communicators do not speak up for their rights, but they know they should. They use tricky ways to show they are upset. Their tone is often read as hostile, since it blends the worst of passive and aggressive styles. Assertive communicators stand up for their own limits and those of others. They weigh their own feelings and the other person feelings, and they speak in a clear, honest way. Their calm air comes from real confidence.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The heart of assertiveness',
        text: 'The most useful result of learning to set boundaries and building emotional intelligence is assertiveness. It is a key tool for talking with others, and it lets you respect your own needs and the needs of others. Assertiveness is about finding the balance between honesty and kindness, while steering clear of aggression or passivity. It is more than a way of talking. It is a mind set that can shape how you think and act.\n\nA core step toward assertiveness is knowing and standing up for your basic rights. That means sharing your feelings, saying no, changing your mind, admitting when you are wrong, and making choices about your life. Assertiveness also means giving others the same rights. Shifting the words you use inside and out is a strong way to change your habits, and the change ripples through every relationship.\n\nA truly assertive person can say no without guilt or unease. The difference between someone who simply talks assertively and someone who is assertive is how they feel inside during the chat. An assertive person respects their needs and the needs of others, in mind and in heart.\n\nAssertiveness is a way of life that blends values, respect, and self knowledge to build healthier ties.\n\nTo set boundaries in an assertive way, follow three golden rules. Be clear and firm from the start. Speak your limits in plain, direct words. If someone crosses a line, say so on the spot. The moment may feel awkward, and the other person may be upset, but firmness stops the same slip from happening again. Apply consequences that fit and stay steady. Crossing a line should bring a clear result, and the result should match the breach. Being late is not the same as being insulted. You decide which cases call for a stronger reply, but you have to be steady. If you are not, no one will take your limits seriously. Set a clear endpoint. The old saying about the third time being the charm works here. If you gave in once or twice, stop on the third try. Letting a pattern take root makes it harder to break later.\n\nRefuse what you need to refuse, and do it as soon as you can, as Publio Siro, a Roman writer from the first century BCE, once said. Assertiveness is a skill that healthcare workers value highly, because they deal with people all day. Nurses and physical therapists give better care when they can handle tense and stressful moments with skill.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Good fences, good neighbors',
        text: 'Assertiveness alone will not make others respect your limits. You also need strong communication habits, with gestures and word choices that show confidence and respect. These skills mix the spoken and unspoken, and they help you set boundaries while keeping your relationships strong.\n\nTo show this, take the case of Sonia and Paula. Sonia is outgoing and lively, and she shows care through touch and is happy to lead any chat. Paula is the opposite. She values her space and feels uneasy when someone interrupts or invades her privacy. The clash starts to wear Paula down and affects her work. One day she decides to speak up and set her limits, but she does it in a way that hurts Sonia more than she meant to. Paula made the right call to set a limit, but her tone was off.\n\nPaula mistake was holding her feelings in for too long. Many people do this to avoid conflict, but the truth is that stuffing feelings only makes them stronger and can damage your ties. Do not be scared to speak up for fear of sounding rude. Clear is better than a pressure cooker that blows up later.\n\nOf the many communication tools you can use, body language is a star. Between 65 and 80 percent of what we share is nonverbal. Posture, eye contact, hand use, and tone of voice all back up the words. When your words clash with your body, the message loses strength.\n\nLet your posture and tone support your words to avoid mixed signals.\n\nAnother strong tool is active listening, which is key to working out limits and reaching deals. It helps you grasp the other person motives and shape your case from what you learn. It also sets a calm mood that builds trust, because the other person feels heard rather than attacked.\n\nA useful tactic is the walkie talkie style, which fixes one of the most common talk problems, accidental cut ins. Setting clear turns to speak lets each side share ideas without being cut off.\n\nYou can also back up the talk with paraphrasing, which means putting the other person ideas into your own words to show that you got the message right.\n\nIt helps to match your style to the moment. In some settings, warmth and care win. In others, calm authority is the right call.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How to make a no stick',
        text: 'Many people find it hard to say no, and they end up in a stress spiral trying to please everyone. It is like taking on too much and finishing nothing, which is draining and frustrating. Time is your most valuable, non renewable resource, and every yes to something you do not care about burns it.\n\nTo start, when you mean to say no, do not give a long reason. We often think not explaining sounds rude, but that is a trap. Most of the time, no one cares why. Giving extra reasons gives others a way to push back. A clean, simple no shows confidence and honesty, and it cuts down on repeat requests. It also helps to take a no from others as a sign of honesty, not a personal slight.\n\nUse this assertive response shape to turn down a request with grace. Begin with a thank you for the invite or the ask. State your no in clear words. Add a short apology if you feel one is needed. Close with a kind or warm line.\n\nFor example, you could say, thank you for thinking of me, but I will not be able to help this time. I am so sorry, and I hope you find a quick solution.\n\nDeliver it in an even, calm tone with steady eye contact. A warm smile adds weight to the message.\n\nIf you are not sure you want to refuse right away, or you think you may change your mind, ask for time to think. That pause lets you weigh the request and avoid later regret. Reflecting first also lowers the chance of feeling guilty about saying no.\n\nWith people who keep pushing, repeat your no without changing the words or adding new reasons. A line like no, thank you, I prefer not to works well. If they still push, reinforce the message with clear body language, like crossed arms or a steady look away. In extreme cases, and depending on the other person rank, a firm do not push is fair game.\n\nSaying no is an investment in your well being and your priorities. Do not be afraid to protect your time, energy, and happiness.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A life free of other people demands',
        text: 'Getting others to respect your limits is a quiet art. The day you understand that you can live without the approval of others, you will be free of their expectations, emotional pressure, and biases.\n\nA useful first step is to send whatever hurts you on its way. Do not let it chip away at your mental health. Work out your rough spots with the people you want to keep close. You will not always agree, and that is fine, but it should not turn them into enemies. Treat your boundaries like you would treat a child. They protect your peace, so make sure others treat them with the care they deserve, and step in to fix breaches when needed.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'company-of-one.json': {
    base: { id: 'company-of-one', title: 'Company of One', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781612921557 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Why growth is not the only path',
        text: 'The phrase the bigger the better has sunk deep into the heart of the business world. If you want more buyers, hire more staff. If you want a global brand, open more offices in hot cities. If revenue is lower than you hoped, pour money into ads, or better yet, throw all your money at one big product.\n\nEach of these steps makes sense on paper, but history has shown that they may not last. Those moves can backfire later. You may need to rethink the habit of leaning on growth as the cure for every business problem.\n\nToo much freedom, in a state or in a person, tends to slip into too much slavery, as Plato once warned. Paul Jarvis believes the pull toward growth is the bane of the business world. He asks, why hire new people when you could reshape the workload and use tech to handle the repeat tasks? He calls this idea the Company of One, a deliberate choice to stay small.\n\nIt sounds backward, but the claim holds water. Growth is not always the right path. Staying small gives you a kind of freedom that big firm leaders miss. It also builds resilience and speed.\n\nInstead of pouring money into expansion, double down on what you do best, and find new ways to lead your corner of the market.\n\nThe Company of One model is a strong way to run a business. It lets you put your core values into the work, which gives birth to a lean, quick firm that can handle a range of economic climates. The plan has three key phases, start small, control growth, and keep learning. Read on to see how you can put this simple, strong plan to work in your own business.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Why simple wins out',
        text: 'The hunger for more has become the default answer for business owners and big firms. One reason some firms never take off is that leaders are no longer happy starting small. Instead of using the freedom that comes with humble roots, they jump straight into the deep end. So the business starts to collapse before it even gets off the ground.\n\nPaul Jarvis also points out that the Company of One model is not just for start ups and solo founders. Mature firms use the model inside key creative teams.\n\nThe Company of One model rests on four key traits. Autonomy, resilience, simplicity, and speed.\n\nResilience is a trait that every business model should show. It keeps a firm from running on wishful thinking. Resilient firms test ideas against the real economic climate.\n\nAutonomy helps a person step past the creative limits of slow, layered systems. This trait gives an owner or founder the freedom to work at their own pace.\n\nOnce autonomy and skill are in place, it gets easier to find faster ways of working, which boosts your speed. The Company of One idea also leans on a love of simplicity. In other words, you cut growth that adds layers to the business.\n\nAfter trimming the noise, the focus can land on what matters, which is serving the customer. The key duty of a business owner is to look after the needs of the buyers you have now, not the millions you wish to have.\n\nA useful fact we often miss is that quality service and good products are the best marketing plan. It also helps to use the flood of new tech that makes remote and quick work possible. Doing so cuts the cost of renting office space and setting up gear for a growing in house team.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The leader in a small firm',
        text: 'In the corporate world, a common belief is that extroverts make the best leaders. The case is easy to see. Extroverts grab attention, and they have the words to make people buy into a goal. But the trait that drives the leadership myth, charisma, can be taught.\n\nA person with no prior hint of charisma can pick it up as a skill. That claim fits with a stronger view that says introverts have what it takes to lead well. Their habit of listening before acting, letting the spotlight fall on others, putting in long quiet hours, and favoring one on one talks are all traits that back up that view.\n\nNo matter where you sit on the introvert or extrovert line, building leadership skill is a must. It will help you in your day to day duties as a team lead, a team member, or a business owner. First, you need to point your autonomy at steady output and profit.\n\nA Company of One still needs leadership. If you work for yourself, you have to lead to pitch your services and keep good ties with customers, as Paul Jarvis notes.\n\nIt also helps to grow a broad set of skills so you understand the fine details of every part of your business. Deep knowledge keeps you in charge of the core work and process.\n\nBeyond skill building, every leader has to learn the mind set that leads to success.\n\nLeaders have to communicate well, build a resilient spirit, and keep their focus. More than that, a leader has to know when to step back, especially when work is hurting relationships and health. As a leader, you have to avoid the downsides of growth that add no real value to the firm.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How purpose drives the work',
        text: 'The question is how to align your drive with the Company of One model. The simple path is to build the Company of One mind set. To do that, you tie your business or career to a purpose, and you let that purpose guide how you handle growth. If your purpose is to give people a well stocked bookstore, then any growth that does not serve that purpose is waste.\n\nBy naming the real reason behind your work, you can build values that support it and use them as the base for every move you make.\n\nIt is important not to mix up your purpose with your passion. The difference is that purpose is a driver, and passion is a hobby. It is tough to build passion for the boring, tedious parts of running a business.\n\nOnce you have found your purpose and pointed your business at it, it gets easier to put your own stamp on the work. People will pick your product over cheaper or flashier brands when your personality comes through in the way you run the business. That point shows that the unique feel of a product often depends on the creative brand and marketing that set it apart.\n\nThe same is true for firms that serve a clear slice of the market and skip the rest. By contrast, brands built on the one size fits all idea do not get the same pull as brands that built a community of like minded users. In other words, products that spark a reaction, good or bad, beat products that are bland and safe.\n\nBy the way, when you stop chasing scale, you can strip the business to its core and find its greatest strength. That is the philosophy of Yvon Chouinard, founder of Patagonia. Business minimalism has helped Patagonia build a strong promise for its products.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Why customer success comes first',
        text: 'More business models are starting to see the role of customer ties in success or failure. Yet a common myth lives on about how to build a trust based link between buyers and firms. Some have taken the human factor out of the loop and use bots for every customer task. Others chase cost cuts.\n\nFor firms that want to use the Company of One model, treat each customer as if they are the only one you have.\n\nInstead of chasing new buyers, focus on keeping the buyers you have. To do that, keep the human touch in your customer work.\n\nThe success of your customers should sit high on your duty list. If your loyal buyers are winning, your firm is likely to win too. Build real empathy for their situation, and do not oversell a product by hyping its features.\n\nIf you want a smooth customer and production system, look at the many ways to meet buyer needs. You can hand some work to partner firms that share your quality bar. You can also use smart tools that personalize service and sort customers.\n\nFor firms that lean on remote workers, the collaboration tools should not pull their team away from the work. Scale back the requirement that workers be online all the time, and ask them to be on call when needed. That change lets staff focus on the main work and lifts the quality of what your firm ships.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Why trust is your best marketing tool',
        text: 'Companies often spend strange amounts on ad campaigns that may not pay off over time. The Company of One mindset takes a different road and focuses on trust. Trust drives sales. It pushes current buyers to send new ones your way, and it shapes an image that puts the customer first.\n\nTo build trust, start with products that focus on a clear niche and match the taste of your buyers. Beyond good products, teaching is a strong marketing tool. When you share useful tips and insight, buyers grow sure of your skill. They value your view, and they pick you over a faceless firm.\n\nEven better, you spend less to reach people who keep coming to your blog or social pages to learn.\n\nReferrals are also a strong marketing tool. Word of mouth only works when your service and products meet a quality bar. You can boost referrals by offering a small reward to people who bring in new buyers.\n\nYou can also set up a rewards plan for loyal buyers, which can push them to tell others about you. As you market the brand and build trust, keep in mind that your current revenue should set the budget for these moves.\n\nDo not spend money you do not have on marketing the product.\n\nWhen it comes to spending, the business stays afloat only if you can hit your minimum viable profit, or MVPr. The lower that number, the faster you reach it. So do what you can to keep the business lean and quick. With that in mind, launch the product as soon as you can.\n\nYou will not learn or earn money by holding the product back. While you build your solution, let simplicity shape the design. Simplicity helps the product sell fast. In other words, solve one clear problem first, then add more features later.\n\nA key point is that it is better to start small than to lean on outside money that can take away your freedom over the design and niche. Building a product that needs the kind of cash only venture capital can offer is a sign that you are tying the business to a complex, shaky model.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A small business can be a strong one',
        text: 'Growth has become the main yardstick for measuring business success. That is the wrong way to think. You do not need a giant building full of workers before you can claim to run a strong company.\n\nIn fact, one reason most founders never win is that they never gave themselves a real shot. They start out trying to live up to the wild growth standard of the corporate world. Instead of pushing yourself to build more and hire more, why not reshape the workload and use tech to handle the repeat tasks? That is where the Company of One model fits in. The model is a deliberate plan to stay small and skip growth for its own sake.\n\nThe truth is that growth is not always the right move. Staying small gives you a kind of freedom that leaders at big firms miss. It also lifts the firm resilience and speed. Resilience helps you make hard calls and keeps you in touch with reality. As a result, when you hit a setback, you will know that giving up is not the answer.\n\nRemember, behind every push for growth or expansion is the urge to spend money you may or may not have. Growth is a popular sign of success, but it does not always mean profit, and profit is the real yardstick for success. A lean model beats a bloated one that drains the people and cash you have.\n\nA useful first step is to weave the Company of One model into your business. Look closely at every part of the operation and find places to cut back. Focus on the core idea that led you to start the business in the first place.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
